summary: Backed stronger enforcement against the illegal importation, distribution, and sale of unauthorized e-cigarettes, including creation/strengthening of a federal multi-agency task force to coordinate enforcement and disrupt illicit networks. Cosponsored the Tobacco TRACE Act to require unique, secure tracking codes on all tobacco products (by June 1, 2026) to strengthen enforcement across the supply chain, trace illicit products back to their source, and crack down on illegal tobacco trafficking.

Gill ties crime directly to immigration and border policy, asserting that a permissive border has allowed 'criminal aliens' into the country and claiming illegal aliens are 'murdering, raping, and pillaging American citizens.' He frames tougher border enforcement and reinstatement of Remain in Mexico as measures to protect public safety. He also cited a recent fraud scandal in Minnesota to argue that unchecked immigration creates acute dangers and threats to public safety in the context of his Somalia moratorium proposal. In September 2025 he introduced and successfully passed the DC Juvenile Sentencing Reform Act in the House (225-203), which lowers the age of eligibility for transfer from juvenile court to felony court from 16 to 14 for specified violent offenses (murder, first-degree sexual abuse, first-degree burglary, armed robbery, and assault with intent). He argued juveniles who commit violent crimes should be tried as adults to protect public safety, increase the number of cases the U.S. Attorney's Office can pursue, and avoid lenient sentences that he says lead to repeat violent offending. He criticized D.C. local reforms as 'pro-crime' and framed federal action as necessary to restore safety in the capital. In November 2025 he introduced the Expedited Removal of Criminal Aliens Act to expand expedited removal authority to violent criminal aliens, mandate detention and swift removal for gang members, terrorists, and those convicted of violent offenses, and make such individuals ineligible for withholding of removalâ€”framing the measure as empowering law enforcement to rapidly remove dangerous foreign nationals to prevent further crimes. In January 2026 he publicly exposed a Minnesota Somali fraud scandal in a House Oversight hearing, alleging Somali organizations had committed waste, fraud, and abuse of welfare programs and funnelled American funds overseas to finance Al Shabaab, and pushed for DOJ prosecutions and accountability. In March 2025 he filed articles of impeachment against Chief Judge James E. Boasberg, accusing the judge of blocking President Trump's invocation of the Alien Enemies Act and thereby preventing the deportation of violent criminal illegal aliens (including alleged gang members), framing the judicial ruling as enabling criminals to remain in the country and as a threat to public safety.

Supported the Epstein Files Transparency Act to compel release of DOJ and related records about the Jeffrey Epstein case, arguing that full transparency is necessary for survivors to obtain justice and for public accountability. Emphasizes that passage requires further action in the Senate, presidential signature, and faithful DOJ implementation. Has also pointed out that delays in seating newly elected Members of Congress (including her own 50-day delay) had the concrete effect of blocking House action on a discharge petition related to the Epstein files, motivating procedural reform to prevent such interference with oversight and accountability. Recently characterized the fatal shooting of Renee Nicole Good by a federal agent as a murder that requires a transparent, accountable investigation and criticized the lack of local participation in a federally-controlled probe into the killing. Has also invoked the killings of Renee Nicole Good and Alex Pretti in calls for accountability and systemic reform of immigration enforcement practices. Most recently called the fatal shooting by an ICE agent in Minneapolis "horrific and deeply troubling," demanding congressional investigation, hearings, and justice. Also condemned the Department of Justice's partial release of the Epstein files as a violation of the Epstein Files Transparency Act, calling the incomplete release an insult to survivors and demanding the Attorney General provide a timeline, explanation, and full compliance with the law. Upon being sworn in she provided the decisive (218th) signature on a discharge petition to force release of the Jeffrey Epstein files and joined survivors Liz Stein and Jessica Michaels in the gallery, underscoring her immediate push for transparency and accountability in high-profile abuse cases.

Co-sponsored the Laken Riley Act (H.R.29) which would require Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) to immediately detain and remove illegal aliens who commit theft offenses; framed the legislation as delivering justice for victims and protecting Georgians in response to the murder of Laken Riley, emphasizing stronger enforcement against criminal offenses by undocumented individuals.
